      <hedline>
        <hl1>When the Talk Is of Faith, What Is the Message?; To Believe or Not</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rabbi Joseph Potasnik letter defends Sen Joseph Lieberman for speaking of greatness of America where one can be both a proud Jew and American simultaneously</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mr. Lieberman's Religious Words'' (editorial, Aug. 31):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mr. Lieberman's Religious Words'' (editorial, Aug. 31):</p>
        <p>It is a most disheartening day in America when the Anti-Defamation League, which speaks of tolerance, says that Joseph I. Lieberman is speaking about religion too much.</p>
        <p>As I listen to Senator Lieberman address the role of religion in America, I hear someone who advocates that one has the right to believe or disbelieve.</p>
        <p>As a rabbi, I have taught that my religion is not better than anyone else's, except that it is better for me. Senator Lieberman has never professed that this should be a Jewish nation or that Judaism be the state religion. Rather he has spoken of the greatness of America where one can be both a proud Jew and American simultaneously. Growing up, I heard that one should be a Jew inside the house and a mensch outside. Senator Lieberman has shown that one can be the same inside and out.</p>
        <p>(Rabbi) JOSEPH POTASNIK  Brooklyn, Aug. 31, 2000</p>
      </block>
